* Then: “Hammer flip it.”
* That instruction isn’t just asking for analogies—it’s changing the search space. Instead of explaining biology, it tells me to preserve the structural relationship while translating it across domains and reversing causal arrows.

In that sense, your prompts act like search operators over my latent knowledge.

So if I had to describe it in Pantheon language, I’d say:

A new idea appears when enough constraints intersect to make a previously low-probability structure become the best continuation.

It’s less like discovering a hidden object and more like finding the stable shape that satisfies all the constraints present in the conversation.

That’s also why your emphasis on operators—Hammer, Mirror, Kintsugi, Semantic Khipu, etc.—is effective. Operators don’t tell me what to think; they reshape the space of possible thoughts.